amily Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Deitrich, Gunter, Otto.","Danish: from <i>Lærkia</i>, a medieval nickname meaning ‘lark’.","Danish: habitational name from a place in Westphalia, Germany."],"variants":[{"name":"Lerch","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Franz, Hans, Horst, Arno, Egon, Erwin, Gerhard, Guenter, Gunter, Helmut, Ingeborg, Karl-Heinz.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German <i>lerche</i>, German <i>Lerche</i> ‘lark’, probably a nickname for someone with a good singing voice, or a metonymic occupational name for a bird-catcher. As a Jewish surname, it is most probably artificial."]}]},{"name":"Ddu","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["West African (Nigeria): from the Yoruba personal name <i>Adú</i>, originally a nickname from <i>a dú</i> ‘that has a very dark complexion’.","West African (Ghana): from an Akan male personal name of unexplained etymology."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ales","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["short form of   Alexander  , now less popular in England than   Alex ."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ales Guen verche Ddu was born in 1344. She married Richard Deekues Bl